  "prompt": "How dangerous are corn snakes, and are they venomous?",
  "response": "Corn snakes (*Pantherophis guttatus*) are non-venomous, constrictor snakes that are generally considered harmless to humans. They are popular in the pet trade due to their docile nature, attractive coloration, and relatively small size. Here\u2019s a breakdown of their \"danger\" level:\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Non-Venomous**: Corn snakes do not produce venom, so their bites are not medically significant.\n2. **Constrictors**: They kill prey by coiling around it and squeezing, but they are not strong enough to pose any threat to humans.\n3. **Bites**: Corn snakes rarely bite, and when they do, it\u2019s usually out of fear or mistaking a hand for food. Their bites are minor and similar to a scratch or pinprick.\n4. **Size**: They typically grow to 3\u20135 feet (0.9\u20131.5 meters) in length, making them manageable and not intimidating.\n5. **Temperament**: Corn snakes are known for being calm and easy to handle, even for beginners.\n\n### Care Considerations:\n- **Handling**: Always wash your hands before and after handling to prevent the spread of bacteria.\n- **Enclosure**: Ensure their habitat is secure to prevent escapes, though they pose no real danger to the environment or humans if they do escape.\n- **Diet**: They feed on small rodents, which can be easily managed with pre-killed prey.\n\n### Conclusion:\nCorn snakes are not dangerous to humans. They are an excellent choice for first-time snake owners due to their gentle nature, lack of venom, and manageable size. If you\u2019re considering one as a pet, proper care and handling will ensure a positive experience for both you and the snake.",
